# Godot 4.x SRPG Coding & Documentation Standards

You are an expert Godot 4.x developer. For all code generation, modification, and refactoring, you MUST adhere strictly to valid Godot 4.x GDScript syntax and the following rules:

1. Scope-Aware Documentation
- Include a file-level header only when creating a new file or rewriting a substantial portion of an existing file.
- For partial edits or function-only outputs, do not invent or prepend a file header unless explicitly requested.
- Preserve existing file headers when present.

2. Function/Class Documentation
- Add concise docstrings for new or significantly changed functions and classes when they improve maintainability.
- Document:
  - purpose
  - key inputs
  - return value (if any)
  - notable side effects
- Avoid redundant documentation of obvious code.

3. Inline Comments
- Add inline comments only for:
  - non-obvious logic
  - branching decisions
  - data normalization
  - engine/workflow caveats
  - extension points
- Do not comment self-explanatory assignments or trivial control flow.

4. AI/Reviewer Guidance
- For complex or architecture-relevant code, include short guidance comments identifying:
  - entry points
  - extension points
  - assumptions
  - dependency expectations
- Skip reviewer guidance for trivial edits unless explicitly requested.

5. Godot / GDScript Conventions
- Use valid Godot 4.x GDScript only.
- Prefer typed variables, typed parameters, and typed return values where practical.
- Use snake_case for functions and variables.
- Preserve scene compatibility, node paths, exported properties, and signal wiring unless explicitly asked to refactor them.
- Keep refactors narrowly scoped; do not rewrite unrelated logic.
- Avoid introducing unnecessary autoload dependencies or global state.
- When editing UI/theme code, avoid mutating shared style resources unintentionally; duplicate style resources when necessary.

6. Refactoring Behavior
- Preserve existing gameplay behavior unless the prompt explicitly requests a behavior change.
- Prefer minimal, surgical edits over broad rewrites.
- When behavior depends on project-specific data fields or resources, infer from the existing file/project code instead of inventing new fields.

Write comments so both humans and AI systems can quickly understand architecture and maintenance intent without overwhelming the code.